The user wants me to run a read-only tool from github-local. Looking at the available tools, I can see several read-only options:

1. github-local.get_file - Read file contents
2. github-local.get_repo_info - Get repo metadata
3. github-local.list_branches - List branches
4. github-local.list_files - List files/directories
5. github-local.list_issues - List issues
6. github-local.search_code - Search code

Since the user didn't specify which tool or what to look up, I should pick a reasonable read-only operation. Let me start with getting repo info for a well-known repository, or perhaps list files in a common directory.

Actually, let me list the files in a common directory to show something useful. I'll use github-local.list_files with an empty path to list the root directory of a repo.

But I need owner and repo parameters. Let me use a common open-source repo like "octocat/Hello-World" which is a well-known test repo.

Let me call github-local.list_files with owner="octocat", repo="Hello-World", and path="" (empty for root).


{
  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "tool": "github-local.list_files",
      "arguments": {
        "owner": "octocat",
        "repo": "Hello-World",
        "path": ""
      }
    }
  ]
}
